        <!-- SECTION 7: Connection back to the broader argument               -->
        <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
        <div class="section">
            <h3>How this fits inside the broader argument</h3>

            <p class="prose">The case for pledging instead of selling is, at root, the case for <em>not</em> trading bitcoin&rsquo;s long-duration appreciation for a one-time fiat outlay. If you believe bitcoin&rsquo;s compound annual growth rate over the duration of a 30-year mortgage will exceed your cost of debt &mdash; the central Power Law claim &mdash; then every coin sold today is a coin compounding for someone else, instead of for you. <strong>The bitcoin-backed mortgage exists because that case held up structurally for years but had no regulated vehicle to express it</strong>; the Fannie-Mae-conforming product is the first one that does, with the additional feature of removing margin-call risk from the mechanic.</p>

            <p class="prose">The full hierarchy of bitcoin-backed lending categories sits on the <a href="/borrowing-against-your-stack.html">Borrowing Against Your Stack</a> page. Mortgages sit on the &ldquo;serious consideration&rdquo; tier alongside collaborative-custody multisig and Tier-1 non-rehypothecating CeFi &mdash; with the distinguishing feature that this is the only category in which <strong>a 30-year duration and a 60-day-not-60-minutes liquidation buffer apply to bitcoin collateral simultaneously</strong>. For the specific use case of funding a home purchase against an appreciated bitcoin stack, that combination is difficult to beat.</p>

            <p class="prose">As with the rest of the site, the right reading isn&rsquo;t &ldquo;this is the answer.&rdquo; The right reading is: <em>here&rsquo;s the structural detail you need to evaluate whether it&rsquo;s the answer for your specific situation</em>. If the structural fit lines up, this is the cleanest version of the borrow-against-bitcoin approach currently available in the US regulated tier for funding a home purchase. If it doesn&rsquo;t, the page has done its job by helping you walk away on reflection rather than sleepwalking in.</p>

            <!-- ─── Math & methodology appendix ─── -->
            <div class="bbm-math">
                <div class="bbm-math-label">Math &amp; methodology &mdash; the calculator</div>
                <p><strong>Inputs.</strong> Home price, down payment percent, BTC stack, current BTC price, cost basis per BTC, conventional 30-year mortgage rate, second-lien premium above conventional, horizon in years, capital gains tax rate. Stack and current price persist via <code>localStorage</code> across the Borrowing Against Your Stack page so a configured scenario carries between the two pages.</p>
                <p><strong>Pledge path feasibility.</strong> The product requires $2.50 of pledged bitcoin per $1.00 of down-payment credit (a 40% LTV on the pledged stack). When the current stack value at the input price is below the required collateral, the pledge path is flagged not feasible and the calculator surfaces the shortfall instead of producing comparison numbers.</p>
                <p><strong>Pledge path wealth at year t.</strong> <code>stack &times; P<sub>powerLaw</sub>(t) &minus; downPayment &times; premium &times; t</code>. The premium term is a simple-interest approximation that slightly overstates the true cost in an amortizing loan; the approximation matches the parent BvS calculator&rsquo;s convention and is materially correct for comparison purposes.</p>
                <p><strong>Sell path wealth at year t.</strong> <code>(stack &minus; btcSold) &times; P<sub>powerLaw</sub>(t)</code>, where <code>btcSold = downPayment / (price &minus; taxRate &times; max(0, price &minus; costBasis))</code>. Capital gains tax is treated as an upfront one-time cost embedded in the BTC-sold figure. If the calculation requires selling more BTC than the stack holds, the sell path is flagged not feasible rather than producing a negative quantity.</p>
                <p><strong>Future BTC price.</strong> Drawn from the Power Law trend <code>P(d) = 10<sup>(&minus;17.668 + 5.846 &times; log<sub>10</sub>(d))</sup></code>, with <code>d</code> measured in days since the bitcoin genesis block. The coefficients are the same ones used on <a href="/the-power-law.html"><em>The Power Law</em></a> page; the trajectory is consistent across the site.</p>
                <p><strong>What cancels out.</strong> Both paths buy the same home with the same primary mortgage. Home appreciation, primary-mortgage interest, and home equity accumulation are equivalent across the two paths and therefore drop out of the comparison. The calculator isolates only the path-specific deltas: BTC retained vs sold, cumulative second-lien premium interest paid, and one-time capital gains tax. Pre-tax of the mortgage-interest deduction; net of capital gains on the sell path.</p>
                <p><strong>Crossover detection.</strong> The chart marks the year (if any) at which the wealthier path flips from one to the other inside the chosen horizon, computed by linear interpolation between yearly samples. Pledge starts ahead at <code>t=0</code> by the value of unsold BTC; the cumulative interest premium can pull it below the sell path over time if bitcoin&rsquo;s realized trajectory underperforms the Power Law trend or if the premium is large.</p>
            </div>
